column5: Likely the earliest traditionally dateable sound change in Carite, and in Indo-European in general, is laryngeal colouring. As its traces can be seen even across Anatolian, it is likely that an allophonic process of vowel colouring next to the traditionally posited laryngeals *hâ‚‚ *hâ‚ƒ predates the Anatolian split. This had little effect on the morphology of Indo-European early on, and only later did it influence its grammatical ablaut. A generalised overview of the process:|-|Two things are notable about this change. The first is that, as in other Indo-European languages, the effects of laryngeal colouring are recoverable only for the vowel *e, and not any other vowel; whether this is due to its effect only on this vowel, or that the effects of colouring on other vowels were lost, is indeterminable. The second is that, after this change, we cannot reliably distinguish in Carite history the laryngeals *hâ‚ and *hâ‚‚ later in time; one theory states that might have merged at some point immediately after colouring effects took place, phonemicising the vowel colour, and another that they remained distinguished, but that sound changes treated them the same due to their phonetic and phonological similarity.
column9:
According to some, Carite also coloured *a next to *hâ‚ƒ:|-|According to those in favour, the colouring of *e next to two different colouring laryngeals can be predicted if the colouring was a two-step process; first, *hâ‚‚ would colour *e to an *a, and this *a would be coloured to *o (alongside uncoloured *e) next to *hâ‚ƒ. However, this environment only appears to appear in a single word (pie@hâ‚‚ehâ‚ƒmÃ³s, whence Â°OOMOSÂ°), which makes it likely another more mainstream explanation can be found.

It is worth noting that while the Latin and Greek reflexes of *hâ‚‚o appear to be either /o/ or /a/, Carite appears to simply reflect *o for these cases.
column12: Voicing assimilation in obstruent clusters is another extremely early Indo-European phenomenon. It predates all the other recoverable processes, and its age relative to laryngeal colouring cannot be determined. The process dictates the spread of voicing from the final element in a cluster regressively.
column14: This change also operated when the cluster included aspirates: they can be assumed to also be voiced, or breathily/partially voiced, to begin with. All aspirates in such clusters presumably become voiceless aspirates, but their result cannot be shown to be different from regular voiced obstruents: presumably, this aspiration is lost early enough internally to merge their outcome with that of regular tenues, and not (the somewhat later) voiceless aspirates.
column15:
This was later generalised to all aspirates before a plosive:|-|This assimilation happened both at morpheme boundaries, and morpheme-internally (especially when triggered by ablaut):

*ni-sáµ’d-Ã³s > Â°NIZDOSÂ°

The voiced consonants produced by this change were generally allophonic, only to phonemicise later when their morphophonological environment became irrecoverable.
column16: A somewhat later process, Siebs' law, changed this system after the rise and proliferation of prefixed s-mobile. Word-initial clusters with |*sB *sBÊ°|, formed morphologically, would devoice, possibly giving rise to a new set of voiceless aspirates, in addition to adding to a growing number of voiceless tenues:|-|It is not clear if the voiceless aspirates remained phonemic for long - in any case, in Carite, they behave identically to the regular voiceless tenues and presumably merged shortly after if they ever were distinct in the first place. Two other large, early processes involving /*s/ took place at roughly the same time.
column17: The first was the dissolution of thorn clusters; all clusters that were underlyingly a sequence of an alveolar and velar plosive were already slightly affricated in earlier Indo-European times (reflected in xlu@Ä«nzagan-, presumably underlyingly /-dzg-/, but not reflected, or possibly undone, in Hittite), but the development of these clusters after the split of Anatolian and Tocharian languages from the main phylum sets the late Common Indo-European group, together with Carite, apart from earlier Indo-European. In Carite, the thorn clusters underwent metathesis and deaffrication:|-|The reflex of |*T{g,Çµ}(Ê·)Ê°| as [*{g,Çµ}(Ê·)Ê°z] is actually expected, since the first part of the intermediate step cluster |*dÊ°g(Ê·)Ê°| (after assimilation) is predictably deaspirated before a plosive, and is then affricated and metathesised.
column26: The degemination of dentals happened similarly to Greek; the first dental (i.e. alveolar plosive) was affricated, and then the resulting cluster was simplified:|-|This process probably only happened only at morpheme boundaries: the pie@Ã¡tta was preserved seemingly unaltered. It is possible that the word had some other process at play, or that it was a babbled word or a loan common to Indo-European; regardless, the process continued to be a productive morphophonological alternation.
column28: Another early process in Carite history, shared with the majority of Indo-European languages, is Osthoff's law, which dictates the shortening of sequences of long vowels followed by a resonant and another, indeterminate consonant:|-|Osthoff's sequences shortened both internally and finally, andâ€”crucial for dating the changeâ€”also happened before laryngeals that were later lost. It is especially important in Carite, being an active surface filter for a greater length of time.
column29: The first big loss of laryngeals (first laryngeal loss) happened immediately after Osthoff's law took place. It dictated the loss of some interconsonantal laryngeals, operating in two different directions:|-|The inherited Indo-European sequences of the type *ÅRHC (including the diphthongs *Åy *Åw, and others) were already shortened and merged into sequences of the type *oRHC due to Osthoff's law.
column31: Centumisation in Carite took place somewhat late, and only after the coalescence of a sequence of a back velar followed by *w into a single labiovelar consonant:|-|Some fringe linguists hypothesise that this change also affected the laryngeal sequence *hâ‚‚w > *hâ‚ƒ, citing late-attested forms such as ?? (from *???) and ?? (hypothetically from *???, though this etymology is controversial). Others dismiss this assumption and claim that *hâ‚‚ had by then merged already with *hâ‚ and that it is indistinguishable from it in these contexts.
column35: Centumisation proper happened quite similarly to how it played out in Greek and Italo-Celtic: the merger of palatovelars into plain velars was straightforward and wasn't followed by any secondary, characteristically satem changes (cf. Germanic and RUKI). Centumisation is taken to have been a single, simple step:|-|Carite is peculiar in that it is possible to recover the identity of the palatovelar series before the labial *w, as they didn't coalesce into a labiovelar, and are instead preserved as *kw *kÊ°w *gw *gÊ°w. This is also present in Greek, which reflects initial *á¸±w as ÎºÏ…- (ku-, as in grc@ÎºÏÏ‰Î½=kÃºÅn 'dog', from pie@á¸±wá¹“; other palatovelars analogously), and (with varying peculiarities) internal *á¸°w as a geminate labiovelar instead of a short one (for example /-kk-/, as in Aeolian grc@á¼´ÎºÎºÎ¿Ï‚=Ã­kkos 'horse', from pie@hâ‚Ã©á¸±wos) .
column39: Immediately following centumisation was labiovelar dissimilation, where many new Carite labiovelars, plenty of which were sourced from coalescent mergers, dissimilated at a distance. Namely, two consecutive syllables were disallowed to have labiovelars in their onsets, forcing a dissimilative loss of rounding:
column40: It was roughly at this point that everyone can agree with the first merger of laryngeals, where *hâ‚ merged with *hâ‚‚. It is assumed the direction of the merger was *hâ‚ > *hâ‚‚ due to the colouring effect the merged laryngeal had on sonorants shortly thereafter. Some linguists prefer calling the laryngeals *hâ‚ *hâ‚’ from this point onwards, referring to their colouring effects, but this usage is not adopted here.
column41: At roughly the same time, the first loss of laryngeals occurred:
column42: One of the changes that lead to the distinguishing of Carite from its now diverging cousins is the vocalisation of sonorants that worked in several stages. The first to be vocalised were sonorants next to a laryngeal:
column48: Next, an epenthetic schwa Indogermanicum was inserted to take up the syllabicity of any remaining sonorant:
column49: The same schwa was inserted after an interconsonantal laryngeal surrounded by true consonants:
column50: Due to the later diphthong reflexes of certain sequences of syllabic laryngeal and semivowel, and their lack of interaction with the preceding consonants, most caritologists also postulate a third schwa-insertion rule:|-|The length of diphthong in question (and, as a result, the position of the schwa relative to the laryngeal) are ultimately irretrievable due to Osthoff's law. The quality of the vowel in early Carite Â°PAWYOSÂ° < pie@phâ‚‚wyÃ³s shows the lack of interaction between the schwa and the first consonant (otherwise, **pÅ«jos would have been expected).
column51: This schwa took up rounding from any previous consonant, though *w curiously enough did not appear to take part in this process, possibly due to its semivocalic nature:
column53: Due to the regressive action of the boukolos rule (Carite does not seem to reflect the progressive version of this law that well, orâ€”according to someâ€”at all), this delabialised any labiovelar after which it occured:

column57: Finally, it lost its distinctiveness by becoming a generic unrounded high vowel:
column58: It is likely that at this point the laryngeals lost differentiation and merged into one general laryngeal continuant, completing the second merger of laryngeals:
column59: The next loss of laryngeals (second laryngeal loss) happened to sequences of vowels with a laryngeal:|-|The lengthening of contracted laryngeal sequences still obeyed Osthoff's law, shortening the new vowels when followed by a resonant and then an obstruent. Examples of this process are scant, but evident in the so-called conjunctive nominals, which, in early Carite, take special forms in subordinated clauses and in coordinated clauses; a typical example of this is the masculine noun Â°EKWOSÂ°, its genitive plural attested both as the regular ekwÅm and in the conjunctive form ekwomfe; the length of the vowel in the suffix is indicative of Osthoff's law.
column61: An unusual, but well-documented Carite change is the effect of laryngeals on consonants in word-initial position. They voiced obstruents and fortified semivowels, probably through a process of glottalisation:|-|A longstanding hypothesis is that the fortition of *Hy resulted in *á¸±, which was still unmerged, but otherwise invisible to historical linguistics. This opinion is somewhat controversial, but unfalsifiable due to our inability to elucidate which exact allophone *y fortited to. This change is occasionally termed Engels' law, and it was first posited by the Limburgish philologist Klaus Engels.
column68: After this, the laryngeals fail to effect any further changes, and are likely lost shortly thereafter, completing the third laryngeal loss:
column69: Word-initial laryngeal voicing of *s enables the dating of another change, its word-initial debuccalisation:
column70: This change was probably concurrent with the deaspiration of obstruents after nasals:
column71: Another concurrent change was the debuccalisation of word-initial prevocalic *gÊ°:|-|It is probable that this change would also have affected word-initial *gÊ·Ê° â†’ *É¦Ê·, but the labiovelarisation of its rounding probably reverted the change shortly thereafter, putting it at â†’ *gÊ·Ê° again.
column72: The collapse of the four-way contrast system followed shortly thereafter. The aspiration feature of voiced aspirates would combine with their voicing to produce a breathy phonation, which merged with voiceless tenues. A possible glottalic interpretation is that in these early Carite stages voicing was a creaky or glottalised feature (explaining laryngeal voicing of word-initial obstruents), and that breathy segments had more in common acoustically with voiceless tenues. column278: The original root noun was clearly archaic and is only preserved in a handful of branches such as Greek. It was later reformed, occasionally as an u-stem but mostly as an o-stem with the later transfer to the fourth declension is because of the feminine gender. The generalisation of Õ¶ (n) in Armenian, which is the word-final reflex of *m, shows that the thematicisation took place after this generalisation had already spread throughout the paradigm. While at a first glance, Carite is isolated in reforming the word as an i-stem, the global remodelling of root nouns as i-stem explains this phenomenon. While u-stems also underwent this transfer, the expected result would have been *domwÄ«. As such, we may convincingly state that Carite, like Armenian, preserved the root noun until the remodelling took place.
